    • Constructor Detail

      • PrimeFactorization

        public PrimeFactorization()
        Default constructor constructs an empty list to represent the number 1. Combined with the add() method, it can be used to create a prime factorization.

      • PrimeFactorization

        public PrimeFactorization(long n)
                   throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Obtains the prime factorization of n and creates a doubly linked list to store the result. Follows the direct search factorization algorithm in Section 1.2 of the project description.
        Parameters:
        n -
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if n < 1

    • Method Detail

      • isPrime

        public static boolean isPrime(long n)
        Test if a number is a prime or not. Check iteratively from 2 to the largest integer not exceeding the square root of n to see if it divides n.
        Parameters:
        n -
        Returns:
        true if n is a prime false otherwise

      • multiply

        public void multiply(long n)
              throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Multiplies the integer v represented by this object with another number n. Note that v may be too large (in which case this.value == OVERFLOW). You can do this in one loop: Factor n and traverse the doubly linked list simultaneously. For details refer to Section 3.1 in the project description. Store the prime factorization of the product. Update value and size.
        Parameters:
        n -
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if n < 1

      • multiply

        public void multiply(PrimeFactorization pf)
        Multiplies the represented integer v with another number in the factorization form. Traverse both linked lists and store the result in this list object. See Section 3.1 in the project description for details of algorithm.
        Parameters:
        pf -

      • dividedBy

        public boolean dividedBy(PrimeFactorization pf)
        Division where the divisor is represented in the factorization form. Update the linked list of this object accordingly by removing those nodes housing prime factors that disappear after the division. No update if this number is not divisible by pf. Algorithm details are given in Section 3.2.
        Parameters:
        pf -
        Returns:
        true if divisible by pf false otherwise

      • dividedBy

        public static PrimeFactorization dividedBy(PrimeFactorization pf1,
                                           PrimeFactorization pf2)
        Divide the integer represented by the object pf1 by that represented by the object pf2. Return a new object representing the quotient if divisible. Do not make changes to pf1 and pf2. No update if the first number is not divisible by the second one.
        Parameters:

        pf2 -
        Returns:

      • gcd

        public PrimeFactorization gcd(long n)
                       throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Computes the greatest common divisor (gcd) of the represented integer v and an input integer n. Returns the result as a PrimeFactor object. Calls the method Euclidean() if this.value != OVERFLOW. It is more efficient to factorize the gcd than n, which can be much greater.
        Parameters:
        n -
        Returns:
        prime factorization of gcd
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if n < 1

      • add

        public boolean add(int p,
                   int m)
        Adds a prime factor p of multiplicity m. Search for p in the linked list. If p is found at a node N, add m to N.multiplicity. Otherwise, create a new node to store p and m. Precondition: p is a prime.
        Parameters:
        p - prime
        m - multiplicity
        Returns:
        true if m >= 1 false if m < 1

      • remove

        public boolean remove(int p,
                      int m)
               throws java.lang.IllegalArgumentException
        Removes m from the multiplicity of a prime p on the linked list. It starts by searching for p. Returns false if p is not found, and true if p is found. In the latter case, let N be the node that stores p. If N.multiplicity > m, subtracts m from N.multiplicity. If N.multiplicity <= m, removes the node N. Precondition: p is a prime.
        Parameters:
        p -
        m -
        Returns:
        true when p is found. false when p is not found.
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if m < 1

      • toString

        public java.lang.String toString()
        Writes out the list as a factorization in the form of a product. Represents exponentiation by a caret. For example, if the number is 5814, the returned string would be printed out as "2 * 3^2 * 17 * 19".
        Overrides:
        toString in class java.lang.Object
